  "response_text": "The concept of supply and demand is a fundamental principle in economics that describes the relationship between the quantity of a product or service that producers are willing and able to produce (supply) and the quantity that consumers are willing and able to buy (demand). This concept is often represented graphically by a supply and demand curve.\n\n**Supply:**\n\nThe supply of a product or service refers to the amount of it that producers are willing and able to produce and sell at a given price level. The supply curve is typically upward-sloping, meaning that as the price of a product increases, the quantity supplied also increases. This is because higher prices make it more profitable for producers to produce more.\n\n**Demand:**\n\nThe demand for a product or service refers to the amount of it that consumers are willing and able to buy at a given price level. The demand curve is typically downward-sloping, meaning that as the price of a product increases, the quantity demanded decreases. This is because higher prices make the",
